Lecture 16 | Predicting Binary Outcomes Using Linear Regression

Today’s Question

In the linear model \(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\), the slope coefficient,\(\hat{\beta}\), can be interpreted as

  1. the predicted Y when X=0
  2. the expected change in the predicted Y when X=0
  3. the predicted Y when X increases by one
  4. the expected change in the predicted Y when X increases by one

Plan for Today

  • Prediction and Linear Regression

  • Example with Binary Outcome Variable:

    • Using Midterm Scores to Predict Probability of Earning an A (includes A and A minus)
  1. Load and explore data
  2. Identify X and Y
  3. What is the relationship between X and Y? (scatter plot and correlation)
  4. Fit a linear model using the least squares method
  5. Interpret coefficients
  6. Make predictions
  7. Measure how well the model fits the data

2. Identify X and Y

  • The predictor (X) is the variable we want to use to predict the outcome (Y)
    • In this case, the predictor is midterm
    • Let’s visualize the distribution of midterm
ggplot(data = data) +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = midterm), bins = 6)

  • The outcome (Y) is the variable that we want to predict
    • In this case, the outcome variable is “gradeA”
    • Let’s visualize the distribution of “gradeA”
ggplot(data = data) +
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = gradeA))
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

  • What type of variable is gradeA?
    • Binary
  • How would you compute the proportion of students who received a grade A (includes A and A minus)?
    • By computing the mean of gradeA
    • Since gradeA is a binary variable, its mean should be interpreted as the proportion of the observations that have the characteristic identified by the variable

  • Code to compute the mean of gradeA
mean(data$gradeA)
## [1] 0.3684211
  • Interpretation?
    • Close to 37% of the students earned an A or A minus in the class
  • RECALL: You need to multiply the output by 100

  • Since Y is binary
    • Unit of measurement of \(\bar{Y}\)?
      • % (after x 100)
    • Unit of measurement of \(\hat{\alpha}\)?
      • % (after x 100)
    • Unit of measurement of \(\hat{Y}\)?
      • % (after x 100)
    • Unit of measurement of \(\bigtriangleup\bar{Y}\)?
      • p.p. (after x 100)
    • Unit of measurement of \(\hat{\beta}\)?
      • p.p. (after x 100)
    • Unit of measurement of \(\bigtriangleup\hat{Y}\)?
      • p.p. (after x 100)

3. What is the relationship between X and Y?

  • Create scatter plot to visualize the relationship between midterm and gradeA
ggplot(data = data) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = midterm, y = gradeA))

  • What does each dot represent?

  • Does the relationship look positive or negative?

  • Does the relationship look weekly or strongly linear?

  • Calculate correlation to measure direction and strength of linear association between midterm and gradeA
cor(data$midterm, data$gradeA)
## [1] 0.6422328

  • We find a moderately strong positive correlation

  • Are we surprised by this?

    • No because in the scatter plot above we observed that the relationship was positive and moderately strongly linear

4. Fit a linear model using the least squares method

  • Recall, R function to fit a linear model: lm()
    • Require argument: a formula of type Y ~ X
lm(gradeA ~ midterm, data = data)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = gradeA ~ midterm, data = data)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)      midterm  
##    -1.34305      0.02122

  • \(\hat{\alpha}\) = -1.34 and \(\hat{\beta}\) = 0.02

  • The fitted line is \(\hat{Y}\) = -1.34 + 0.02X

  • More specifically, it is \(\hat{gradeA} = -1.34 + 0.02midterm\)

  • R function to add fitted line to scatter plot: abline() or geom_smooth()
fit <- lm(gradeA ~ midterm, data = data)


#tidyverse
ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = midterm, y = gradeA)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

#base R
plot(data$midterm, data$gradeA)
abline(fit, color = "blue")
## Warning in int_abline(a = a, b = b, h = h, v = v, untf = untf, ...): "color" is
## not a graphical parameter

5. Interpretation of Coefficients:

  • Substantive interpretation of \(\hat{\alpha}\)

    • Start with mathematical definition:
      • \(\hat{\alpha}\) is \(\hat{Y}\) when X = 0
    • When a student scores 0 points in the midterm, we predict that their probability of earning an A in the class is -134% on average

  • Sometimes it is nonsensical (due to extrapolation)

  • Unit of measurement of \(\hat{\alpha}\)

    • Same as \(\bar{Y}\)
    • In this case, Y is binary and measured in points, so \(\bar{Y}\) is measured in % and so is \(\hat{\alpha}\)

  • Substantive interpretation of \(\hat{\beta}\)
    • \(\hat{\beta}\) is the \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) associated with a\(\bigtriangleup \hat{X}\) = 1
    • An increase in midterm scores of 1 point is associated with a predicted increase in the probability of earning an A in the class of 2 percentage points on average
  • Unit of measurement of \(\hat{\beta}\)
    • Same as \(\bigtriangleup \bar{Y}\)
    • In this case, Y is binary so \(\bigtriangleup \bar{Y}\) is measure in p.p and so is \(\hat{\beta}\)

  • The Fitted Line Is

\(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\)

  • \(\hat{\alpha}\) (alpha-hat) is the estimated intercept coefficient the \(\hat{Y}\) when X = 0

  • \(\hat{\beta}\) (beta-hat) is the estimated intercept coefficient the \(\bigtriangleup \bar{Y}\) when \(\bigtriangleup \bar{X}\) = 1

  • Using the Fitted Line to Make Predictions

  • There are two types of predictions that we might be interested in

    • Predict \(\hat{Y}\) based on X: \(\hat{Y} = \hat{\alpha} + \hat{\beta}X\)
    • Predict \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) associated with \(\bigtriangleup X\): \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) = \(\hat{\beta}\bigtriangleup X\)

6. Make Predictions

  • Example 1: Imagine you earn 80 points in the midterm, what would we predict your probability of earning an A in the class to be?
\(\hat{final} = -1.34 + 0.02midterm\)
\(\hat{final} = -1.34 + 0.02 \times 80\) (if midterm = 80)
\(\hat{final} = 0.26\)

  • Therefore, if you earn 80 points in the midterm, we would predict that your probability of earning an A in the class is of 26% on average

  • In this case, Y is binary and measure in %

  • Example 2: Imagine you earn 90 points in the midterm, what would we predict your probability of earning an A in the class to be?
\(\hat{final} = -1.34 + 0.02midterm\)
\(\hat{final} = -1.34 + 0.02 \times 90\) (if midterm = 90)
\(\hat{final} = 0.46\)
  • Therefore, if you earn 90 points in the midterm, we would predict that your probability of earning an A in the class is of 46% on average

  • To predict \(\bigtriangleup \bar{Y}\) associated with \(\bigtriangleup X\): \(\bigtriangleup \hat{Y}\) = \(\hat{\beta}\bigtriangleup X\)

  • Example 3: If you increase your midterm scores by 10 points, by how much would we predict that your gradeA exam scores would change?

\(\bigtriangleup\hat{final} = 0.02\bigtriangleup midterm\)
\(\bigtriangleup\hat{final} = 0.02 \times 10\) (if \(\bigtriangleup\) midterm = 10)
\(\bigtriangleup\hat{final} = 0.2\)
  • Therefore, an increase of midterm scores of 10 points is associated with a predicted increase in the probability of earning an A in the class f 20 percentage points

7. Measure how well the model fits the data with \(R^2\)

  • How good is the model at making predictions? How well does the model fit the data?

  • One way of answering is by calculating \(R^2\)

  • \(R^2\) measures the proportion of the variation in the outcome variable explained by the model

    • It ranges from 0 to 1
    • The higher the better the model fits the data
    • In the simple linear model: \(R^2 = cor(X, Y)^2\)
    • The higher the correlation between X and Y (in absolute terms) the better the model fits the data

  • When cor(X,Y) = 1 or cor(X,Y) = -1, the relationship between X and Y is perfectly linear

  • \(R^2\) = cor(X,Y)2 = 1, the model explains 100% of the variation of Y

  • All prediction errors (vertical distance between the dots and the line) = 0

  • When cor(X,Y) = 0, the relationship between X and Y is non-linear

  • \(R^2\) = cor(X,Y)2= 0, the model explains 0% of the variation of Y

  • The prediction errors (vertical distance between the dots and the line) are very large

#tidyverse
ggplot(data = data, mapping = aes(x = midterm, y = gradeA)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

  • Let’s compute \(R^2\)
cor(data$midterm, data$gradeA)^2
## [1] 0.4124629
#check
